description:
Round 2 gap analysis: Missed because the overflow check seems reasonable at first glance.

At lines 356-358:
```c
if (consecutive_errors < INT_MAX) {
    consecutive_errors++;
}
```

And at lines 361-364:
```c
if (consecutive_errors > 0 && consecutive_errors % RX_ERROR_WARN_THRESHOLD == 0) {
    LOG_WRN("LoRa RX: %d consecutive errors - check hardware",
            consecutive_errors);
}
```

The INT_MAX cap is overkill - RX_ERROR_WARN_THRESHOLD is 5, and warnings occur every 5 errors. Even at 1 error per second, reaching INT_MAX would take ~68 years. The cap adds complexity for no practical benefit.

More importantly, once consecutive_errors hits INT_MAX and stays there, the modulo check (consecutive_errors % 5 == 0) will always be false (INT_MAX % 5 = 2), so warnings stop permanently. This is arguably a bug if the intent was to keep warning.

Suggestion: either remove the cap (let it overflow - who cares at that point) or reset to a base value when hitting MAX.
